### Zoom-out workflow (v3.4.1) — when encountering an unknown module

You are doing project recon and you stumbled upon a file/module whose
purpose is not clear from its direct content. Do NOT dive into it line by line.
Zoom out:

1. **Map callers** — run `Grep` or Bash:
   ```
   Grep -r "from <module>" {{PROJECT_ROOT}}/.icm-main/src/
   Grep -r "import <module>" {{PROJECT_ROOT}}/.icm-main/src/
   ```
   List 3-5 main callers. Do not cite all — only the representative ones.

2. **Identify 1 caller that looks like the "root"** — usually the one
   at the top of the call graph (least called by others). Read that caller first.

3. **Note new terms in recon-report** — any technical names
   (classes, functions, domain concepts) that appeared during this
   zoom-out should become ubiquitous language candidates. Add section
   `### Glossary candidates` to `output/recon-report.md`. Stage 01 will
   resolve these into official entries in `_config/CONTEXT.md`.

4. **Do not document the module now** — recon is not design. Only record:
   "Module X is touched by callers A, B, C. Deepen in stage 01 (discovery)
   if relevant to the workspace objective." Skipping details avoids
   spending context on irrelevant code.

5. **Explicit limit** — if zoom-out requires more than 3 levels of
   indirection (caller → caller → caller), stop. Note in recon-report:
   "Depth > 3 — investigation deferred to stage 01 on demand".

Anti-pattern: reading an unknown file line by line without context. Costs
context without proportional gain. Recon is a map, not exploration.
